column3: able: (usually followed by `to') having the necessary means or skill or know-how or authority to do something; "able to swim"; "she was able to program her computer"; "we were at last able to buy a car"; "able to get a grant for the project"
entity: that which is perceived or known or inferred to have its own distinct existence (living or nonliving)
a cappella: without musical accompaniment; "they performed a cappella"
breathe, respire, suspire, take a breath: draw air into, and expel out of, the lungs; "I can breathe better when the air is clean"; "The patient is respiring"
thing: a separate and self-contained entity
annoyingly: in an annoying manner or to an annoying degree
however: in whatever way or manner; "Victory, however it was brought about, was sweet"; "however he did it, it was very clever"
as such, in and of itself, intrinsically, per se: with respect to its inherent nature; "this statement is interesting per se"
enrollment, enrolment, registration: the act of enrolling
tear: fill with tears or shed tears; "Her eyes were tearing"
aurally: with regard to sound or the ear; "the new musical was visually and aurally appealing"
shock: subject to electrical shocks
fall back, lapse, recidivate, regress, relapse, retrogress: go back to bad behavior; "Those who recidivate are often minor criminals"
conjuration, conjuring trick, deception, illusion, legerdemain, magic, magic trick, thaumaturgy, trick: an illusory feat; considered magical by naive observers
ambitionless, unambitious: having little desire for success or achievement
ringer: (horseshoes) the successful throw of a horseshoe or quoit so as to encircle a stake or peg
unresentful: not resentful; "completely unresentful and forgiving"
for all the world, for any price, for anything, for love or money: under any circumstances; "she wouldn't give up her pets for love or money"
vertical bank: a bank so steep that the plane's lateral axis approaches the vertical
roll: a flight maneuver; aircraft rotates about its longitudinal axis without changing direction or losing altitude
put on: add to something existing; "She put on a sun room"
extravagantly, lavishly, richly: in a rich and lavish manner; "lavishly decorated"
help: improve; change for the better; "New slipcovers will help the old living room furniture"
helplessly, impotently, unable to help: in a helpless manner; "the crowd watched him helplessly"
boringly, tediously, tiresomely: in a tedious manner; "boringly slow work"; "he plodded tediously forward"
spin-dry: dry (clothes) by spinning and making use of centrifugal forces
north, northerly, northward, northwards: in a northern direction; "they earn more up north"; "Let's go north!"
blasphemously: in a blasphemous manner; "the sailors were cursing blasphemously"
lighten, lighten up: become lighter; "The room lightened up"
stain: produce or leave stains; "Red wine stains the table cloth"
hitch, hobble, limp: the uneven manner of walking that results from an injured leg
dejectedly, in low spirits: in a dejected manner; "when she came back Sophie and Esther were sitting dejectedly in the kitchen"
daintily: in a refined manner; "she nibbled daintily at her cake"
blood transfusion, transfusion: the introduction of blood or blood plasma into a vein or artery
alpinism: mountain climbing (not restricted to the Alps)
overtaking, passing: going by something that is moving in order to get in front of it; "she drove but well but her reckless passing of every car on the road frightened me"
idiotically: in an idiotic manner; "what arouses the indignation of the honest satirist is not the fact that people in positions of power or influence behave idiotically"
metamorphose, transform, transmute: change in outward structure or looks; "He transformed into a monster"; "The salesman metamorphosed into an ugly beetle"
blend, coalesce, combine, commingle, conflate, flux, fuse, immix, meld, merge, mix: mix together different elements; "The colors blend well"
moodily: in a moody manner; "in the bar, a youngish, sharp-eyed man was staring moodily into a gin and tonic"
spill: reduce the pressure of wind on (a sail)
shabbily: in a mean and ungenerous manner; "the two were haggling shabbily in the drawing-room"
perfuse, suffuse: cause to spread or flush or flood through, over, or across; "The sky was suffused with a warm pink color"
telescopically: in a telescopic manner; "each of the four legs contains a simple screw jack with a thrust bearing that is operated telescopically inside of two tubes"
thermostatically: by thermostat; in a thermostatic manner; "the temperature is thermostatically controlled"
drown: kill by submerging in water; "He drowned the kittens"
under: into unconsciousness; "this will put the patient under"
judicially: as ordered by a court
encrimson: make crimson
draw, hook, hooking: a golf shot that curves to the left for a right-handed golfer; "he took lessons to cure his hooking"
lifework: the principal work of your career
audit: attend academic courses without getting credit
attend to, take to heart: get down to; pay attention to; take seriously; "Attend to your duties, please"
incorrupt: free of corruption or immorality; "a policeman who was incorrupt and incorruptible"
craniotomy: a surgical opening through the skull
microsurgery: surgery using operating microscopes and miniaturized precision instruments to perform intricate procedures on very small structures
scheme: devise a system or form a scheme for
follow, trace: follow, discover, or ascertain the course of development of something; "We must follow closely the economic development is Cuba" ; "trace the student's progress"
malpractice: professional wrongdoing that results in injury or damage; "the widow sued his surgeon for malpractice"
interview: go for an interview in the hope of being hired; "The job candidate interviewed everywhere"
catnap, cat sleep, forty winks, nap, short sleep, snooze: sleeping for a short period of time (usually not in bed)
athletics: participation in sports events as an extracurricular activity
fmri, functional magnetic resonance imaging: a form of magnetic resonance imaging of the brain that registers blood flow to functioning areas of the brain
sequence: determine the order of constituents in; "They sequenced the human genome"
get off: deliver verbally; "He got off the best line I've heard in a long time"
enumerate, itemise, itemize, recite: specify individually; "She enumerated the many obstacles she had encountered"; "The doctor recited the list of possible side effects of the drug"
announce, declare: announce publicly or officially; "The President declared war"
call: utter a characteristic note or cry; "bluejays called to one another"
drive home, press home, ram home: make clear by special emphasis and try to convince somebody of something; "drive home a point or an argument"; "I'm trying to drive home these basic ideas"
howl, roar: make a loud noise, as of wind, water, or vehicles; "The wind was howling in the trees"; "The water roared down the chute"
quarterback: play the quarterback
disqualification: the act of preventing someone from participating by finding them unqualified
win: be the winner in a contest or competition; be victorious; "He won the Gold Medal in skating"; "Our home team won"; "Win the game"
curtailment, suppression: the act of withholding or withdrawing some book or writing from publication or circulation; "a suppression of the newspaper"
auto-da-fe: the burning to death of heretics (as during the Spanish Inquisition)
overextend, overstrain: strain excessively; "He overextended himself when he accepted the additional assignment"
competence hearing: a hearing to determine legal capacity (to determine whether the defendant can understand the charges and cooperate with a lawyer in preparing a defense)
smear: stain by smearing or daubing with a dirty substance
carve, chip at: engrave or cut by chipping away at a surface; "carve one's name into the bark"

battle of little bighorn, battle of the little bighorn, custer's last stand, little bighorn: a battle in Montana near the Little Bighorn River between United States cavalry under Custer and several groups of Native Americans (1876); Custer was pursuing Sioux led by Sitting Bull; Custer underestimated the size of the Sioux forces (which were supported by Cheyenne warriors) and was killed along with all his command

battle of the philippine sea, philippine sea: a naval battle in World War II (1944); a decisive naval victory for the United States fleet over the Japanese who were trying to block supplies from reaching American troops on Leyte
tsushima: a naval battle in the Russo-Japanese War (1905); the Japanese fleet defeated the Russian fleet in the Korean Strait
punic war: one of the three wars between Carthage and Rome that resulted in the destruction of Carthage and its annexation by Rome; 264-241 BC, 218-201 BC, 149-146 BC
lapidate, stone: kill by throwing stones at; "People wanted to stone the woman who had a child out of wedlock"
salmonella: rod-shaped Gram-negative enterobacteria; cause typhoid fever and food poisoning; can be used as a bioweapon
sea tang, tang: any of various coarse seaweeds
unliveried: not wearing livery; "an unliveried chauffeur"
bosom, embrace, hug, squeeze: squeeze (someone) tightly in your arms, usually with fondness; "Hug me, please"; "They embraced"; "He hugged her close to him"
genus leuciscus, leuciscus: a genus of fish including: dace, chub
resift: sift anew
overcharge, overload, surcharge: place too much a load on; "don't overload the car"
little skate, raja erinacea: most plentiful skate in North American inshore waters in summer; to 21 inches
chock up, cram, jam, jampack, ram, wad: crowd or pack to capacity; "the theater was jampacked"
carduelis carduelis, goldfinch: small European finch having a crimson face and yellow-and-black wings
wash out: wash free from unwanted substances, such as dirt; "Wash out your dirty shirt in the sink"
take in, take up: accept; "The cloth takes up the liquid"
erithacus, genus erithacus: Old World thrushes
strain, tense: become stretched or tense or taut; "the bodybuilder's neck muscles tensed;" "the rope strained when the weight was attached"
clinch: hold a boxing opponent with one or both arms so as to prevent punches
fix: set or place definitely; "Let's fix the date for the party!"

labyrinthodonta, labyrinthodontia, superorder labyrinthodonta, superorder labyrinthodontia: extinct amphibians typically resembling heavy-bodied salamanders or crocodiles and having a solid flattened skull and conical teeth; Devonian through Triassic
sculpt, sculpture: create by shaping stone or wood or any other hard material; "sculpt a swan out of a block of ice"
stage direct: direct for the stage
sonoran lyre snake, trimorphodon lambda: of desert regions of southwestern North America
asian coral snake: of India
carrion: the dead and rotting body of an animal; unfit for human food
aranea, araneus, genus aranea, genus araneus: a genus of orb-weaving spiders including common garden spiders and barn spiders
die: languish as with love or desire; "She dying for a cigarette"; "I was dying to leave"
intimidate, restrain: to compel or deter by or as if by threats
stooge: cruise in slow or routine flights
aythya ferina, pochard: heavy-bodied Old World diving duck having a grey-and-black body and reddish head
cradle: hold or place in or as if in a cradle; "He cradled the infant in his arms"
tramp: cross on foot; "We had to tramp the creeks"
buck, hitch, jerk: jump vertically, with legs stiff and back arched; "the yung filly bucked"
glide: move smoothly and effortlessly
myaceae, order myaceae: clams
acorn barnacle, balanus balanoides, rock barnacle: barnacle that attaches to rocks especially in intertidal zones
lead, precede: move ahead (of others) in time or space
derail, jump: run off or leave the rails; "the train derailed because a cow was standing on the tracks"
family turnicidae, turnicidae: small Old World birds resembling but not related to true quail
order sphenisciformes, sphenisciformes: penguins
giant fulmar, giant petrel, macronectes giganteus: large brownish petrel chiefly of Antarctic seas
gutter: flow in small streams; "Tears guttered down her face"
nose, scent, wind: catch the scent of; get wind of; "The dog nosed out the drugs"
bruchus, genus bruchus: type genus of the Bruchidae

discern, distinguish, make out, pick out, recognise, recognize, spot, tell apart: detect with the senses; "The fleeing convicts were picked out of the darkness by the watchful prison guards"; "I can't make out the faces in this photograph"
soldier: a wingless sterile ant or termite having a large head and powerful jaws adapted for defending the colony
alien, alienate: transfer property or ownership; "The will aliened the property to the heirs"
negociate: transfer by endorsement to another in return for value received; "negociate a bond"
cryptotermes, genus cryptotermes: genus of dry wood termites; cosmopolitan in distribution; sometimes considered a subgenus of Kalotermes
bid: make a serious effort to attain something; "His campaign bid for the attention of the poor population"
black market, run: deal in illegally, such as arms or liquor
liquidate: settle the affairs of by determining the debts and applying the assets to pay them off; "liquidate a company"
derequisition: release from government control
divert, hive off: withdraw (money) and move into a different location, often secretly and with dishonest intentions
snag: get by acting quickly and smartly; "snag a bargain"
aided, assisted: having help; often used as a combining form
genus thomomys, thomomys: western pocket gophers
reflectorise, reflectorize: provide with reflectors, such as chemicals; "the driveway was reflectorized for safety reasons"
naked mole rat: fetal-looking colonial rodent of East Africa; neither mole nor rat; they feed on tubers and have a social structure similar to that of honeybees and termites
dun: horse of a dull brownish grey color
anoa, anoa depressicornis, dwarf buffalo: small buffalo of the Celebes having small straight horns
stag: adult male deer
care, deal, handle, manage: be in charge of, act on, or dispose of; "I can deal with this crew of workers"; "This blender can't handle nuts"; "She managed her parents' affairs after they got too old"
little spotted skunk, spilogale putorius, spotted skunk: small skunk with a marbled black and white coat; of United States and Mexico
anteater, new world anteater: any of several tropical American mammals of the family Myrmecophagidae which lack teeth and feed on ants and termites
genus loxodonta, loxodonta: a genus of Elephantidae
peristome: region around the mouth in various invertebrates
batrachoididae, family batrachoididae: toadfishes; related to anglers and batfishes
secular, temporal, worldly: characteristic of or devoted to the temporal world as opposed to the spiritual world; "worldly goods and advancement"; "temporal possessions of the church"
get at: influence by corruption
zonal: associated with or divided into zones; "a zonal pattern of cell structure"; "zonal division"

begin, start: have a beginning characterized in some specified way; "The novel begins with a murder"; "My property begins with the three maple trees"; "Her day begins with a workout"; "The semester begins with a convocation ceremony"
eke out: live from day to day, as with some hardship; "He eked out his years in great poverty"
bead: form into beads, as of water or sweat, for example
ascitic: of or relating to or resulting from an abnormal accumulation of protein and electrolyte rich fluid in the peritoneal cavity
benzylic: relating to benzyl
act as: function as or act like; "This heap of stones will act as a barrier"
carbonyl, carbonylic: relating to or containing the carbonyl group

continue, cover, extend: span an interval of distance, space or time; "The war extended over five years"; "The period covered the turn of the century"; "My land extends over the hills on the horizon"; "This farm covers some 200 acres"; "The Archipelago continues for another 500 miles"
amphibian, amphibious vehicle: a flat-bottomed motor vehicle that can travel on land or water
curricular: of or relating to an academic course of study
erythropoietic: of or relating to the formation of red blood cells
fenestral: of or relating to windows
filar: related to or having filaments (especially across a field of view as in the eyepiece of a telescope); "a filar eyepiece"
graphic: of or relating to the graphic arts; "the etchings, drypoints, lithographs, and engravings which together form his graphic work"- British Book News
chasidic, chassidic, hasidic, hassidic: of or relating to the Jewish Hasidim or its members or their beliefs and practices
hidrotic: of or relating to sweat
living: pertaining to living persons; "within living memory"
nazarene: of or relating to the town of Nazareth or its inhabitants
balmoral: a sturdy laced walking shoe
semiotic, semiotical: of or relating to semiotics; "semiotic analysis"
bass: the member with the lowest range of a family of musical instruments
basset horn: a tenor clarinet; pitched in the key of F below the B-flat clarinet
tibial: relating to or located near a tibia
billiard ball: ball used in playing billiards
bosporus bridge: a suspension bridge across the Bosporus at Istanbul
boudoir: a lady's bedroom or private sitting room
bread knife: a knife used to cut bread
colloidal: of or relating to or having the properties of a colloid
latitudinal: of or relating to latitudes north or south
bronx-whitestone bridge: a suspension bridge across the East River in New York City
anthropological: of or concerned with the science of anthropology; "anthropological studies"
astrophysical: of or concerned with astrophysics; "astrophysical sciences"
buckle: fastener that fastens together two ends of a belt or strap; often has loose prong
american: of or relating to or characteristic of the continents and islands of the Americas; "the American hemisphere"; "American flora and fauna"
camlet: a fabric of Asian origin; originally made of silk and camel's hair
carnegie mellon university: an engineering university in Pittsburgh
operculate, operculated: having an operculum
rheologic, rheological: of or relating to rheology
cither, cithern, citole, cittern, gittern: a 16th century musical instrument resembling a guitar with a pear-shaped soundbox and wire strings
closet auger: a snake used to unblock toilets
coach, coach-and-four, four-in-hand: a carriage pulled by four horses with one driver
crew neck, crew neckline: a plain straight neckline opening from shoulder to shoulder of sweaters
cricket equipment: sports equipment used in playing cricket
deflector: a device intended to turn aside the flow of something (water or air or smoke etc)
distributor housing: the housing that supports the distributor cam
divining rod, dowser, dowsing rod, waterfinder, water finder: forked stick that is said to dip down to indicate underground water or oil
elbow: a length of pipe with a sharp bend in it
emesis basin: a basin used by bedridden patients for vomiting
fuel system: equipment in a motor vehicle or aircraft that delivers fuel to the engine
graphic art: the arts of drawing or painting or printmaking
hack: a tool (as a hoe or pick or mattock) used for breaking up the surface of the soil
illustration: a visual representation (a picture or diagram) that is used make some subject more pleasing or easier to understand
clioquinol, iodochlorhydroxyquin: drug used to treat certain fungal infection (as athlete's foot)
japan: lacquer with a durable glossy black finish, originally from the orient
length: a section of something that is long and narrow; "a length of timber"; "a length of tubing"

clipper, limiter: (electronics) a nonlinear electronic circuit whose output is limited in amplitude; used to limit the instantaneous amplitude of a waveform (to clip off the peaks of a waveform); "a limiter introduces amplitude distortion"
maxi: a long skirt ending below the calf
measure: a container of some standard capacity that is used to obtain fixed amounts of a substance
musnud: a seat with a cushion that is used as a throne by Indian princes
neosporin: trade name for a topical drug containing several antibacterials; used as an ointment for skin irritations and in the form of eyedrops for minor eye infections
notions counter: counter where notions are sold
oriflamme: a red or orange-red flag used as a standard by early French kings
pile, piling, spile, stilt: a column of wood or steel or concrete that is driven into the ground to provide support for a structure
plastron: a metal breastplate that was worn under a coat of mail
power saw, saw, sawing machine: a power tool for cutting wood
printer: (computer science) an output device that prints the results of data processing
replica, replication, reproduction: copy that is not the original; something that has been copied
roof: protective covering on top of a motor vehicle
searing iron: a hot iron used to destroy tissue
security system: (computing) a system that enforces boundaries between computer networks
semi-abstraction: a semiabstract painting
skep: a domed beehive made of twisted straw
socket: receptacle where something (a pipe or probe or end of a bone) is inserted
souk: an open-air market in an Arabian city
speaking tube: a tube for conveying the sound of a voice from one room to another
spline: a flexible strip (wood or rubber) used in drawing curved lines
depot, entrepot, storage, store, storehouse: a depository for goods; "storehouses were built close to the docks"
tile: a flat thin rectangular slab (as of fired clay or rubber or linoleum) used to cover surfaces
t-square: a square used by draftsmen to draw parallel lines
ventilator: a device (such as a fan) that introduces fresh air or expels foul air
water jacket: a container filled with water that surrounds a machine to cool it; especially that surrounding the cylinder block of an engine
window shade: an opaque window blind that can cover or uncover a window
yoke: support consisting of a wooden frame across the shoulders that enables a person to carry buckets hanging from each end
exquisiteness: extreme beauty of a delicate sort
appeal, appealingness, charm: attractiveness that interests or pleases or stimulates; "his smile was part of his appeal to her"
loftiness, majesty, stateliness: impressiveness in scale or proportion
progressiveness, progressivity: advancement toward better conditions or policies or methods
unpalatability, unpalatableness: the property of being unacceptable to the mind; "the policy's unpalatability caused an uproar"
coyness, demureness: the affectation of being demure in a provocative way
religiousness: the quality of being extremely conscientious; "his care in observing the rules of good health amounted to a kind of religiousness"
unconscientiousness: the quality of being willing to ignore the dictates of conscience
prankishness, rascality, roguishness: the trait of indulging in disreputable pranks
viscosity, viscousness: resistance of a liquid to shear forces (and hence to flow)
white, whiteness: the quality or state of the achromatic color of greatest lightness (bearing the least resemblance to black)
gray, grayness, grey, greyness: a neutral achromatic color midway between white and black

quality, timber, timbre, tone: (music) the distinctive property of a complex sound (a voice or noise or musical sound); "the timbre of her soprano was rich and lovely"; "the muffled tones of the broken bell summoned them to meet"
magnetisation, magnetization: the physical property of being magnetic
lateness: quality of coming late or later in time
latitude: scope for freedom of e.g. action or thought; freedom from restriction
right to an attorney: a civil right guaranteed by the 6th amendment to the US Constitution
germ: a small apparently simple structure (as a fertilized egg) from which new tissue can develop into a complete organism
aortic plexus: a plexus of lymph nodes in the lower portion of the abdominal aorta
fundus: (anatomy) the base of a hollow organ or that part of the organ farthest from its opening; "the uterine fundus"; "the fundus of the stomach"
cartilage bone: any bone that develops within cartilage rather than a fibrous tissue
perimysium: the sheath of connective tissue that covers a bundle of muscle fibers
ciliary body: the part of the tunic of the eye between the choroid coat and the iris; "the ciliary body produces aqueous humor"
intima: the innermost membrane of an organ (especially the inner lining of an artery or vein or lymphatic vessel)
arteria glutes, gluteal artery: branches of the internal iliac artery that supply the hip joint and gluteal region
haversian canal: any of the many tiny canals that contain blood vessels and connective tissue and that form a network in bone
alveolar bed: lung tissue densely packed with alveoli
proprioceptor: special nerve endings in the muscles and tendons and other organs that respond to stimuli regarding the position and movement of the body
lumbosacral plexus: a nerve plexus formed by the ventral divisions of the coccygeal and sacral and lumbar nerves; supplies the lower limbs and perineum and coccygeal area
male reproductive system: the reproductive system of males
cervical glands, cervical glands of the uterus, glandulae cervicales uteri: mucus-secreting glands in the mucosa of the uterine cervix
naris: any of the openings to the nasal cavities that allow air to flow through the cavities to the pharynx
housecraft: skill in domestic management
protocol: code of correct conduct; "safety protocols"; "academic protocol"
sense: a general conscious awareness; "a sense of security"; "a sense of happiness"; "a sense of danger"; "a sense of self"
guesstimate, guestimate: an estimate that combines reasoning with guessing

romanesque, romanesque architecture: a style of architecture developed in Italy and western Europe between the Roman and the Gothic styles after 1000 AD; characterized by round arches and vaults and by the substitution of piers for columns and profuse ornament and arcades
zero, zero point: the point on a scale from which positive or negative numerical quantities can be measured
chaotic attractor, strange attractor: an attractor for which the approach to its final point in phase space is chaotic
apparition, fantasm, phantasm, phantasma, phantom, shadow: something existing in perception only; "a ghostly apparition at midnight"
point: the object of an activity; "what is the point of discussing it?"
edification, sophistication: uplifting enlightenment
space-time, space-time continuum: the four-dimensional coordinate system (3 dimensions of space and 1 of time) in which physical events are located
serology: the branch of medical science that deals with serums; especially with blood serums and disease
comparative literature: study of literary works from different cultures (often in translation)
lit crit, literary criticism: the informed analysis and evaluation of literature
dialectology: the branch of philology that is devoted to the study of dialects
gazette: a newspaper or official journal
senor: a Spanish title or form of address for a man; similar to the English `Mr' or `sir'
mistranslation: an incorrect translation
pop-up, pop-up book: a book (usually for children) that contains one or more pages such that a three-dimensional structure rises up when a page is opened
unabridged, unabridged dictionary: a dictionary that has not been shortened by the omitting terms or definitions; a comprehensive dictionary
itinerary, travel guidebook: a guidebook for travelers
finger alphabet, manual alphabet: an alphabet used by the deaf; letters are represented by finger positions
insurance, insurance policy, policy: written contract or certificate of insurance; "you should have read the small print on your policy"
bill of attainder: a legislative act finding a person guilty of treason or felony without a trial; "bills of attainder are prohibited by the Constitution of the United States"
comic book: a magazine devoted to comic strips
jump cut: an immediate transition from one scene to another
canon: a rule or especially body of rules or principles generally established as valid and fundamental in a field or art or philosophy; "the neoclassical canon"; "canons of polite society"
master of education, med: a master's degree in education
fourteenth amendment: an amendment to the Constitution of the United States adopted in 1868; extends the guarantees of the Bill of Rights to the states as well as to the federal government
hairline: a very thin line
choreography: a notation used by choreographers
f: the 6th letter of the Roman alphabet
l: the 12th letter of the Roman alphabet
roulade: (music) an elaborate run of several notes sung to one syllable
baritone, baritone voice: the second lowest adult male singing voice
sight: anything that is seen; "he was a familiar sight on the television"; "they went to Paris to see the sights"
solresol: an artificial language
shina: a Dardic language spoken in northern Kashmir
badaga: the dialect of Kannada that is spoken by the Badaga
xhosa: a Bantu language closely related to Zulu
secondo: the second or lower part of a duet (especially a piano duet)
gregorian chant, plainchant, plainsong: a liturgical chant of the Roman Catholic Church
cantus firmus: a melody used as the basis for a polyphonic composition
serenade: a song characteristically played outside the house of a woman
epanodos: repetition of a group of words in reverse order
expletive: a word or phrase conveying no independent meaning but added to fill out a sentence or metrical line
contradiction, contradiction in terms: (logic) a statement that is necessarily false; "the statement `he is brave and he is not brave' is a contradiction"
system command: a computer user's instruction (not part of a program) that calls for action by the computer's executive program
war cloud: an ominous sign that war threatens
sequella: a secondary consequence
cycle, oscillation: a single complete execution of a periodically repeated phenomenon; "a year constitutes a cycle of the seasons"
carnot cycle, carnot's ideal cycle: a cycle (of expansion and compression) of an idealized reversible heat engine that does work without loss of heat
atavism, reversion, throwback: a reappearance of an earlier characteristic
thunder: a booming or crashing noise caused by air expanding along the path of a bolt of lightning
resolution: the subsidence of swelling or other signs of inflammation (especially in a lung)
grand slam: winning all of the tricks in a hand of bridge
care, concern, fear: an anxious feeling; "care had aged him"; "they hushed it up out of fear of public reaction"
canned meat, tinned meat: meat preserved in a can or tin
gazpacho: a soup made with chopped tomatoes and onions and cucumbers and peppers and herbs; served cold
pepper pot, philadelphia pepper pot: a soup made with vegetables and tripe and seasoned with peppercorns; often contains dumplings
dragee: sugar-coated nut or fruit piece
flummery: a bland custard or pudding especially of oatmeal
german pancake, pfannkuchen: puffy mildly sweet lemon-flavored egg mixture sprinkled with confectioners' sugar and served with jam or a wine or fruit sauce
pin bone: part of the sirloin between the flat bone and the porterhouse
cacao bean, cocoa bean: seed of the cacao tree; ground roasted beans are source of chocolate
ribier: dark reddish-purple table grape of California
spice: any of a variety of pungent aromatic vegetable substances used for flavoring food
tabasco, tabasco sauce: very spicy sauce (trade name Tabasco) made from fully-aged red peppers
butter: an edible emulsion of fat globules made by churning milk or cream; for cooking and table use
garlic butter: butter seasoned with mashed garlic
hot stuffed tomato, stuffed tomato: tomato cases filled with various mixtures and baked briefly
people: (plural) any group of human beings (men or women or children) collectively; "old people"; "there were at least 200 people in the audience"
carload: a gathering of passengers sufficient to fill an automobile
